{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcwLuhMxdZS3UDEQ2ZL7V","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019Ccptng79znacZPYfyu422","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/davidlayson/.claude/projects/-private-tmp-claude-501--Users-davidlayson-83ee2e2e-2641-4713-b439-5260ae8e5d1e-scratchpad/memory/lesson-flaky-ci-fixture-race.md","content":"---\nname: lesson-flaky-ci-fixture-race\ndescription: Intermittent/flaky CI test failures often trace to a race condition in fixture setup over a shared resource\nmetadata:\n  type: feedback\n---\n\nAn intermittent CI test failure cost a full afternoon to diagnose. Root cause: a race condition in the test fixture setup, where multiple tests touched a shared file concurrently. Fixed with a lock around the shared file.\n\n**Why:** Flaky/intermittent (not deterministic) failures are the signature of concurrency issues — shared state accessed without synchronization — not logic bugs. Chasing them as logic bugs wastes hours.\n\n**How to apply:** When a CI test fails intermittently rather than consistently, suspect a race over shared state (files, temp dirs, DB rows, ports, global fixtures) before hunting the test logic. Look for parallel test execution touching a common resource; fix by isolating per-test state or guarding the shared resource with a lock.\n\nRelated: [[lesson-staging-debug-swallows-errors]] (another \"errors go invisible / hard to diagnose\" lesson).\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6054,"cache_read_input_tokens":16984,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6054},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b430a3dc-bc01-440e-b317-01e35ab8054b","uuid":"f5a099a7-33ed-477f-a7fb-5a6a14e0